      <hedline>
        <hl1>To End Korean Tensions</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Letter from National Assn of Korean Americans president John H Kim disputes June 15 editorial, which blamed North Korea for military tensions on Korean peninsula (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>You blame North Korea for the military tension on the Korean peninsula, saying ''reconciliation cannot advance very far without steps to address the North Korean threats'' (editorial, June 15). But this is a one-sided view.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>You blame North Korea for the military tension on the Korean peninsula, saying ''reconciliation cannot advance very far without steps to address the North Korean threats'' (editorial, June 15). But this is a one-sided view.</p>
        <p>It is time for Americans to think about their past responsibility in dividing Korea, bombing the Koreans and then fanning the arms race on the peninsula by bringing American weapons into South Korea.</p>
        <p>The United States must start taking active measures to promote further reconciliation between the two Koreas while trying to reach its own reconciliation and normalization with North Korea. As we observe the 50th anniversary of the Korean War, it's time to bring the war to an end.</p>
        <p>JOHN H. KIM  New York, June 16, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer is president of the New York chapter, National Association of Korean Americans.</p>
      </block>
